     <body>
        <div type="spain">
           <pb facs="#zone_Page_130" n="130"/>
           <fw>75</fw>
           
           <ab><date>1810</date> VOYAGE TO <rs type="place" ref="#lisbon">LISBON</rs></ab>
           <ab>4 Days all but 3 or 4 hours Thermometer below 60</ab>
           <ab><date>October Tuesday 23. 1810</date> Plymouth Cremill<note type="editorial_note">i.e. Cremyll Ferry, across the Tamar between Plymouth and Mount Edgcumbe</note> passage.</ab>
           <ab>Go on board the Poictiers 74 <rs type="person" ref="#john_beresford">Cap Beresford<note type="editorial_note">Probably John Beresford (1766-1844), later 1st Baronet, brother of Sir William, the future 1st Viscount Beresford. John was certainly in the navy at the time, and this Captain Beresford is Sir William's brother.</note></rs> about 4. Sail about 6 from <rs type="place" ref="#cawsand_bay">Causand<note type="translation">Cawsand</note> bay </rs>
              <date>Wednesday24</date> at 12 off <rs type="place" ref="#ushant">Ushant</rs>. cold. high sea Wind fair. <date>Thursday 25 Oct</date> latitude 
              4o6:5’0. <date>Friday 26</date> of <rs type="place" ref="#cape_finisterre">Cape Finisterre</rs> having a run of 240 miles in 24 hours 
              <date>Saturday 27th</date> <rs type="place" ref="#mondego">Mondego</rs> off <rs type="place" ref="#berlengas">Berlengas</rs> at 12. See the palace of <rs type="place" ref="#mafra">Mafra</rs>. About 2 a pilot 
              came on board in an old boat with 2 other men. The oars made of 2 poles 
              on which a deal board was tied. the sail <figure facs="#zone_Page_130_47cb3ec1-756b-4918-93eb-33fc7199968d" type="in_text"><note type="editorial_note">[drawing: boat]</note></figure>. A decayed walnut shell mended 
              with a wafer box, a most dangerous tattered vehicle. The man began by sayin <choice><abbr>d-</abbr><expan>damn</expan></choice> my eyes. 
              and assured us the French had sent flags of truce requesting a cessation of hostilities which <rs type="person" ref="#ld_wellington">Ld Wellington</rs> would not 
              grant.</ab>
           <ab>Anchor in the bay of <rs type="place" ref="#cascais">Cascayes<note type="translation">Cascais</note></rs></ab>
           
           <figure facs="#zone_Page_130_6ec8b1ff-b5e6-4cef-9933-172799bc989c">
              <note type="editorial_note">Pen and ink drawing: Palace of <rs type="place" ref="#mafra">Mafra</rs></note>
              <label>PALACE OF <rs type="place" ref="#mafra">MAFRA</rs> <date>27 Octob 1810</date></label>
           </figure>
           
           <ab>Entering the <rs type="place" ref="#tagus">Tagus</rs> the country 
              on the north bank is very ugly &amp; 
              barren. without trees.</ab>
           
           <ab>On the south where the high land joins the sand is the Village of <rs type="place" ref="#trafaria">Tariffa<note type="translation">Trafaria</note></rs></ab>
           <figure facs="#zone_Page_130_19b10fdd-4b0b-4647-8361-c186dfc1854d" type="in_text">
              <note type="editorial_note">Pen and ink drawing: windmill</note>
              <label>Portuguese Windmill</label>
           </figure>
           
           <ab><date>October 28</date> pass up the <rs type="place" ref="#tagus">Tagus</rs> by the <rs type="place" ref="#castle_st_julians">Castle of St Julians</rs> <choice><abbr>L</abbr><expan>left</expan></choice>, the fort 
              Bugia <choice><abbr>R</abbr><expan>right</expan></choice>.<note type="translation">the Fort of São Julião da Barra left, the Fort of São Lourenço do Bugio right</note> A long line of Sand stretches from the Southern shore towd the fort. 
              <choice><abbr>L</abbr><expan>left</expan></choice> a mirador<note type="translation">viewpoint</note> of the King, having passed in a valley a palace of <rs type="person" ref="#henriquez_tuera">Count 
                 Henriquez Tuera</rs> with gardens &amp; Trees.</ab>
           
           <figure facs="#zone_Page_130_5200462d-1e52-46c1-a8d2-d5905fce4b80">
